\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
1.1.2 The current situation of the taxation of international aviation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Taxes on flights are low in all countries in comparison with other goods
 (Keen and Strand 2006) and taxes on international flights are particularly
 low.
 Globally, the airport charges are estimated to be below marginal costs
 (Keen and Strand 2006), constituting an implicit subsidy.
 The Atkinson-Stiglitz theorem suggests therefore that the marginal costs
 of public funds are lower than for typical other taxes.
 However, these are global welfare results.
 Tax competition amongst countries vying for visitors (Keen, Strand 2006)
 can still explain why it might not be in any one country's interest to
 unilaterally increase typical taxes such as ticket taxes.
 In part 2 we will obtain some results that suggest that there is another
 global efficiency gain that could be realized through taxes to the extent
 that they increase the load factors for flights.
 It is also an open question as to whether social surplus could be increased
 through the use of per-plane taxes which would lead to larger planes being
 employed by airlines, which cost less fuel per available seat (Swan, Adler
 2006).
 In appendix 4 we develop a model that can give an answer to this question.
 If there indeed such market failures, then taxes on vacant seats per plane
 taxes and to a much lesser extent carbon taxes can correct them.
 These efficiency gains would be distinct from the climate change externality.
 They are internal to the markets where load factors are increased and larger
 airplanes are used.
 Also, they would mean that the marginal costs of public funds as born by
 the individual countries are on average lower for such taxes than for the
 currently used ticket taxes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If these results from part 2 are correct, then the question arises why countries
 have not already introduced tax instruments such as per-plane taxes and
 taxes on vacant seats to address the abovementioned internal market failures.
 Legal obstacles could explain the suboptimal level and kind of taxes currently
 in place.
 For example, in his 2011 Budget speech the then UK Chancellor, George Osborne,
 conceded that 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

we had hoped that we could replace the per passenger tax with a per plane
 tax.
 We have tried every possible option, but have reluctantly had to accept
 that all are currently illegal under international law.
 So we will work with others to try to get that law changed.
