\begin_layout Standard
2.0.1 Motivation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the global warming externality was the only market failure in the aviation
 market, then a carbon tax and a VAT would be sufficient instruments to
 implement the social optimum (Keen, Strand 2006).
 There is thus some burden of proof for any alternative proposal of tax
 instruments.
 The UK government seems to have been convinced (HM Treasury 2008) that
 a per-plane-tax could increase efficiency (by increasing load factors)
 when it tried to implement it in 2010 but abandoned the project due to
 international legal obstacles.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The following questions arise: What would be the vector of optimal tax rates
 if a per-plane-tax and a tax on vacant seats were introduced? What welfare
 improvements, if any, could be achieved? These tax instruments would affect
 the outcome along the following central dimensions: Firstly, the size of
 aircrafts employed and secondly the load factors on flights.
 Any model aiming to answer these questions must therefore at least adequately
 represent how the outcomes are determined across these two dimensions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
2.0.2 Specificities of the air travel market
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The literature on the optimal taxation of air travel has applied general
 equilibrium theory (Keen, Strand 2006).
 However, there are certain specificities of the air travel market that
 have to be taken into account when considering a wider set of tax instruments.
 Importantly, a flight ticket becomes valueless after the departure of the
 flight.
 Each airline faces at each point in time the trade-off between either lowering
 the posted price so as to sell additional tickets or to increase it so
 as to get more revenue in case of a sale and also so as to have more tickets
 left to sell in case demand turns out to be high later on.
 However, since the demand process is inherently stochastic, it might turn
 out that few customers will appear to consider taking the flight.
 In this case the airline will end up leaving potentially many seats empty.
 In fact, around 20 percent of seats remain empty on average globally (IATA
 2016).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
2.03 Existing literature on the optimal taxation of air travel
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Keen Strand 2006 have analysed the optimal choice between ticket taxes and
 taxes on the externalities in a general equilibrium model.
 However, this approach does not allow us to analyse taxes on vacant seats
 or per-plane taxes.
 McAfee, te Velde (2006, 2008) analyse social welfare in a dynamic pricing
 model and conclude that profit maximisation by the monopolist will lead
 to welfare maximisation.
 However, we will show that if one calibrates the model so as to yield the
 observed load factors of 80% welfare maximisation under monopoly can only
 be achieved through a tax on vacant seats.
 The associated welfare gains turn out to be 3.2%.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For calculating optimal tax rates for per-plane taxes it will be crucial
 to capture well the `size-frequency trade-off' for social welfare: On the
 one hand larger airplanes result in lower costs per seat (Swan, Adler 2006),
 on the other hand higher flight frequency associated with smaller airplanes
 confer welfare benefits to consumers.
 To avoid analytical difficulties, Brueckner and Flores-Fillol (2006) use
 a reduced form approach for analyzing the welfare economics of the size-frequen
cy tradeoff, concluding that the duopolistic outcome is an inefficiently
 low frequency.
 However, it is doubtful whether the reduced form approach should be given
 much credence.
 In section 2 we will develop oligopolistic dynamic pricing models with
 endogenous aircraft choice that could yield a more adequate analysis and
 which allow the calculation of optimal rates for per-plane taxes.
\end_layout

