\begin_inset Formula $g\left(t\right)\selectlanguage{greek}\frac{\text{dy}\left(t\right)}{\text{dα}}\selectlanguage{english}$
\end_inset

 which is not defined in terms of the other variables.
 However, we have the profit optimality condition
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
+g\left(z\right)\left(1-\frac{1}{\epsilon\left(z\right)}+\frac{\epsilon^{^{\prime}}\left(z\right)}{y^{^{\prime}}\left(z\right)}\frac{y\left(z\right)}{\epsilon\left(z\right)^{2}}\right)=n\left(z\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Ultimately, we have just one `dimension': If we had just given the distribution
 of valuations then everything is determined.
 We have one more constraint in the form of the definition of the elasticity:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
epsilon\left(z\right)=\frac{\text{dD}}{\text{dy}}\frac{y}{D}=\frac{D^{^{\prime}}\left(z\right)}{y^{^{\prime}}}\frac{y}{D}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We also get one more constraint from the profit maximization:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
^{^{\prime}}\left(z\right)-\frac{y^{^{\prime}}\left(z\right)}{\epsilon\left(z\right)}+\epsilon^{\prime}\left(z\right)\frac{y\left(z\right)}{\epsilon\left(z\right)^{2}}=-\lambda D\left(t\right)\left(y\left(t\right)-c\right)+h^{^{\prime}}\left(z\right)\left(y\left(z\right)-c-\frac{y\left(z\right)}{\epsilon\left(z\right)}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus we have the 9 variables 
\begin_inset Formula $h,m,q,r,n,\epsilon,y,D,g$
\end_inset

 and the above 8 constraints on them and their first derivatives.
 We can normalize
\begin_inset Formula $c=1$
\end_inset

.
 From the literature we know the ratio of the highest price ever charged
 to the marginal cost 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

, which gives us an initial condition 
\begin_inset Formula $y\left(0\right)=y_{0}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We also have that the vacancy rate equals the observed vacancy rate
\begin_inset Formula $v^{*}$
\end_inset

 and that the ratio of the average price 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{*}$
\end_inset

 to the marginal cost equals the observed value.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
^{*}=1-A\left(T\right)=1-\exp\left(-\selectlanguage{greek}\int_{s=0}^{T}{\text{λD}\left(y\left(s\right)\right)}\selectlanguage{english}\text{ds}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
^{*}=\selectlanguage{greek}\frac{\int_{s=0}^{T}{y\left(s\right)}\text{λD}\left(y\left(s\right)\right)\exp\left(-\int_{t=0}^{s}{\text{λD}\left(y\left(t\right)\right)}\text{dt}\right)\text{ds}}{\selectlanguage}{greek}\selectlanguage{english}{\int_{s=0}^{T}{\text{λD}\left(y\left(s\right)\right)\exp\left(-\int_{t=0}^{s}{\text{λD}\left(y\left(t\right)\right)}\text{dt}\right)\text{ds}}}\selectlanguage{english}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Upon rewriting these two conditions give us two isoperimetric constraints
 for our variational problem:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
-v^{*}=\exp\left(-\selectlanguage{greek}\int_{s=0}^{T}{\text{λD}\left(y\left(s\right)\right)}\selectlanguage{english}\text{ds}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
=\selectlanguage{greek}\int_{s=0}^{T}{\text{λD}\left(s\right)}\selectlanguage{english}\text{ds}-log(\frac{1}{1-v^{*}})
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
=\int_{s=0}^{T}{(\lambda D\left(s\right)-\frac{1}{T}\log\left(\frac{1}{1-v^{*}}\right))ds}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
^{*}\selectlanguage{greek}\int_{s=0}^{T}{\lambda D\left(y\left(s\right)\right)\exp\left(-\int_{t=0}^{s}{\text{λD}\left(y\left(t\right)\right)}\text{dt}\right)\text{ds}}\selectlanguage{english}=\int_{s=0}^{T}{y\left(s\right)}\selectlanguage{greek}\text{λD}\selectlanguage{english}\left(y\left(s\right)\right)\exp\left(-\selectlanguage{greek}\int_{t=0}^{s}{\text{λD}\left(y\left(t\right)\right)}\selectlanguage{english}\text{dt}\right)\text{ds}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\selectlanguage{greek}int_{s=0}^{T}{\left(p^{*}-y\left(s\right)\right)\text{λD}\left(s\right)\exp\left(-\int_{t=0}^{s}{\text{λD}\left(t\right)}\text{dt}\right)\text{ds}}\selectlanguage{english}=0
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\selectlanguage{greek}int_{s=0}^{T}{\left(p^{*}-y\left(s\right)\right)\text{λD}\left(s\right)\exp\left(-h(s)\right)\text{ds}}\selectlanguage{english}=0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us denote the Lagrange multiplier associated with the isoperimetric
 constraint
\begin_inset Formula $0=\selectlanguage{greek}\int_{s=0}^{T}{\text{λD}\left(s\right)}\selectlanguage{english}\text{ds}-log(\frac{1}{1-v^{*}})$
\end_inset

as 
\begin_inset Formula $l_{v}$
\end_inset

 and that associated with the isoperimetric constraint
\begin_inset Formula $\selectlanguage{greek}\int_{s=0}^{T}{\left(p^{*}-y\left(s\right)\right)\text{λD}\left(s\right)\exp\left(-h(T)\right)\text{ds}}\selectlanguage{english}=0$
\end_inset

as 
\begin_inset Formula $l_{p}$
\end_inset

.
 For all the instantaneous constraints we shall denote the (time dependent)
 Lagrange multipliers by adding a subscript
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Lagrangian now becomes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
=\selectlanguage{greek}\text{gλ}\selectlanguage{english}\exp\left(-h\right)\left(-D-\frac{D^{^{\prime}}}{y^{\prime}}q\right)+l_{v}\left(\selectlanguage{greek}\text{λD}\selectlanguage{english}\left(s\right)-\frac{1}{T}\log\left(\frac{1}{1-v^{*}}\right)\right)+l_{p}\left(\left(p^{*}-y\right)\selectlanguage{greek}\text{λD}\selectlanguage{english}\exp\left(-h\right)\right)+a_{h}\left(h^{^{\prime}}-\lambda D\right)+a_{m}\left(m^{^{\prime}}+Dy^{^{\prime}}\right)+a_{q}\left(q^{^{\prime}}+\lambda\ m\right)+a_{r}\left(r^{^{\prime}}-\frac{\lambda D^{^{\prime}}}{y^{^{\prime}}}g\right)+a_{n}\left(n^{^{\prime}}-h^{^{\prime}}n+g\left(\lambda D^{^{\prime}}\left(y-1\right)+\lambda D\right)-\lambda D\left(y-1\right)\text{\ r}\right)+a_{g}\left(1+g\left(1-\frac{1}{\epsilon}+\frac{\epsilon^{^{\prime}}}{y^{^{\prime}}}\frac{y}{\epsilon^{2}}\right)-n\right)+a_{\epsilon}\left(\epsilon-\frac{D^{^{\prime}}}{y^{^{\prime}}}\frac{y}{D}\right)+a_{\pi}\left(y^{^{\prime}}-\frac{y^{^{\prime}}}{\epsilon}+\epsilon^{^{\prime}}\frac{y}{\epsilon^{2}}+\lambda D\left(y-c\right)-h^{^{\prime}}\left(y-c-\frac{y}{\epsilon}\right)\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here the 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{h},a_{m},a_{q},a_{r},a_{n},a_{g},a_{\epsilon},a_{\pi}\ $
\end_inset

are the time-varying Lagrange multipliers of the instantaneous constraints.
 By interpreting D as a demand intensity we can simplify the notation by
 redefining D to be 
\lang greek
λ
\lang english
D
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
=g\exp\left(-h\right)\left(-D-\frac{D^{^{\prime}}}{y^{\prime}}q\right)+l_{v}\left(D-\frac{1}{T}\log\left(\frac{1}{1-v^{*}}\right)\right)+l_{p}\left(\left(p^{*}-y\right)D\exp\left(-h\right)\right)+a_{h}\left(h^{^{\prime}}-D\right)+a_{m}\left(m^{^{\prime}}+Dy^{^{\prime}}\right)+a_{q}\left(q^{^{\prime}}+m\right)+a_{r}\left(r^{^{\prime}}-\frac{D^{^{\prime}}}{y^{^{\prime}}}g\right)+a_{n}\left(n^{^{\prime}}-h^{^{\prime}}n+g\left(D^{^{\prime}}\left(y-1\right)+\lambda D\right)-\lambda D\left(y-1\right)\text{\ r}\right)+a_{g}\left(1+g\left(1-\frac{1}{\epsilon}+\frac{\epsilon^{^{\prime}}}{y^{^{\prime}}}\frac{y}{\epsilon^{2}}\right)-n\right)+a_{\epsilon}\left(\epsilon-\frac{D^{^{\prime}}}{y^{^{\prime}}}\frac{y}{D}\right)+a_{\pi}\left(y^{^{\prime}}-\frac{y^{^{\prime}}}{\epsilon}+\epsilon^{^{\prime}}\frac{y}{\epsilon^{2}}+D\left(y-c\right)-h^{^{\prime}}\left(y-c-\frac{y}{\epsilon}\right)\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can freely choose the following 4 initial conditions:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(0\right),y^{^{\prime}}\left(0\right),D\left(0\right),D^{^{\prime}}\left(0\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
And we can see from the constraints that for each of the other variables
 we obtain the value at either 0 or T and the value of its first derivative
 at 0.
 We can now compute the Euler-Lagrange equations for this variational problem.
 We can then define a function that for given values of
\begin_inset Formula $M,y\left(0\right),y^{^{\prime}}\left(0\right),D\left(0\right),D^{^{\prime}}\left(0\right)$
\end_inset

solves the system of system of Euler-Lagrange equations by finding the values
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $l_{v}$
\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula $l_{p}$
\end_inset

 that result in the two isoperimetric constraints being satisfied.
 We can then minimize this function over the set of possible values for
\begin_inset Formula $y\left(0\right),y^{^{\prime}}\left(0\right),D\left(0\right),D^{^{\prime}}\left(0\right)$
\end_inset

.
 This minimal value is thus a function solely of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 We can then find the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $M^{\#}$
\end_inset

 such that this minimum is 0.
 We can then deduce: If 
\begin_inset Formula ${M\leq M}^{\#}$
\end_inset

 then a marginal increase in the tax on vacant seats starting from 0 is
 always welfare-increasing, whatever the distribution of valuations consistent
 with the observed vacancy rate and the observed ratio of average prices
 to marginal costs.
\end_layout

